Here's a simple Java program that implements RSA encryption and decryption:

```java
import java.math.BigInteger;
import java.security.SecureRandom;

public class RSA {

  private final static BigInteger one = new BigInteger("1");
  private final static SecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();

  private BigInteger privateKey;
  private BigInteger publicKey;
  private BigInteger modulus;

  // generate an N-bit (decimal) prime
  private static BigInteger generatePrime(int N) {
    return BigInteger.probablePrime(N, random);
  }

  // generate keys
  public RSA(int N) {
    BigInteger p = generatePrime(N);
    BigInteger q = generatePrime(N);
    BigInteger phi = (p.subtract(one)).multiply(q.subtract(one));

    modulus = p.multiply(q);
    publicKey = new BigInteger("65537"); // common value in practice = 2^16 + 1
    privateKey = publicKey.modInverse(phi);
  }

  // encrypt message
  public BigInteger encrypt(BigInteger message) {
    return message.modPow(publicKey, modulus);
  }

  // decrypt message
  public BigInteger decrypt(BigInteger encrypted) {
    return encrypted.modPow(privateKey, modulus);
  }

  // return string representation of keys
  public String toString() {
    String s = "";
    s += "public  = " + publicKey + "\n";
    s += "private = " + privateKey + "\n";
    s += "modulus = " + modulus;
    return s;
  }

  // test program
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    int N = Integer.parseInt(args[0]);
    RSA key_pair = new RSA(N);
    System.out.println(key_pair);

    // encrypt and decrypt a message
    BigInteger message = new BigInteger(N-1, random);
    BigInteger encrypted = key_pair.encrypt(message);
    BigInteger decrypted = key_pair.decrypt(encrypted);
    System.out.println("message   = " + message);
    System.out.println("encrypted = " + encrypted);
    System.out.println("decrypted = " + decrypted);
  }
}
```

To use this program, you can create a new instance of the `RSA` class with an integer parameter `N`, which determines the bit length of the prime numbers used to generate the keys. Then you can call the `encrypt()` method to encrypt a `BigInteger` message, and the `decrypt()` method to decrypt the result.

The `toString()` method returns a string representation of the public and private keys, and is useful for debugging and testing. The `main()` method shows an example usage of the RSA implementation, generating a random message and encrypting and decrypting it using the generated keys.

Here's a simple Java program that uses SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) to send an email:

```java
import java.util.*;
import javax.mail.*;
import javax.mail.internet.*;

public class SendEmail {

  public static void main(String[] args) {

    String smtpHost = "smtp.gmail.com";
    String fromEmail = "your_email@gmail.com";
    String fromPassword = "your_password";
    String toEmail = "recipient_email@gmail.com";
    String subject = "Test Email";
    String messageBody = "This is a test email sent from Java.";

    Properties properties = System.getProperties();
    properties.setProperty("mail.smtp.host", smtpHost);
    properties.put("mail.smtp.auth", "true");
    properties.put("mail.smtp.starttls.enable", "true");
    properties.put("mail.smtp.port", "587");

    Session session = Session.getDefaultInstance(properties, new Authenticator() {
      protected PasswordAuthentication getPasswordAuthentication() {
        return new PasswordAuthentication(fromEmail, fromPassword);
      }
    });

    try {
      MimeMessage message = new MimeMessage(session);
      message.setFrom(new InternetAddress(fromEmail));
      message.addRecipient(Message.RecipientType.TO, new InternetAddress(toEmail));
      message.setSubject(subject);
      message.setText(messageBody);

      Transport.send(message);
      System.out.println("Email sent successfully.");
    } catch (MessagingException ex) {
      System.err.println("Failed to send email: " + ex.getMessage());
    }
  }

}
```

To send an email, you need to specify the SMTP server address (e.g., "smtp.gmail.com" for Gmail), your email address and password, the recipient email address, the email subject and message body.

The program uses the `javax.mail` package to create a `MimeMessage` object, set its properties (using the `setFrom()`, `addRecipient()`, `setSubject()` and `setText()` methods), and send it using the `Transport.send()` method. The `Authenticator` class is used to provide the email address and password for authentication.

To receive email with SMTP, you could use a similar approach, but you would need to modify the program to connect to the mailbox using POP3 or IMAP, and retrieve the email messages using the `javax.mail` package.

Here's a simple Java program that uses IMAP (Internet Message Access Protocol) to receive email:

```java
import java.util.*;
import javax.mail.*;
import javax.mail.internet.*;

public class ReceiveEmail {

  public static void main(String[] args) {

    String imapHost = "imap.gmail.com";
    String username = "your_email@gmail.com";
    String password = "your_password";

    Properties properties = new Properties();
    properties.setProperty("mail.store.protocol", "imaps");
    properties.setProperty("mail.imap.host", imapHost);
    properties.setProperty("mail.imap.port", "993");

    try {
      Session session = Session.getDefaultInstance(properties, null);
      Store store = session.getStore("imaps");
      store.connect(imapHost, username, password);

      Folder inbox = store.getFolder("INBOX");
      inbox.open(Folder.READ_ONLY);

      Message[] messages = inbox.getMessages();
      System.out.println("Number of messages: " + messages.length);

      for (int i = 0; i < messages.length; i++) {
        Message message = messages[i];
        System.out.println("---------------------------------");
        System.out.println("Email #" + i + ":");
        System.out.println("Subject: " + message.getSubject());
        System.out.println("From: " + message.getFrom()[0]);
        System.out.println("Text: " + message.getContent().toString());
      }

      inbox.close(false);
      store.close();
    } catch (MessagingException | IOException ex) {
      System.err.println("Failed to receive email: " + ex.getMessage());
    }
  }

}
```

To receive email with IMAP, you need to specify the IMAP server address (e.g., "imap.gmail.com" for Gmail), your username and password.

The program uses the `javax.mail` package to create a `Session` object, connect to the server using the `Store.connect()` method, open the `INBOX` folder using the `Store.getFolder()` method, and retrieve the email messages using the `Folder.getMessages()` method. 

The program displays the number of messages retrieved, and for each message, it displays the subject, sender and contents of the message.

Note that you need to have the JavaMail API and JavaBeans Activation Framework (JAF) libraries in your classpath to run this program. You can download them from the following links:

- JavaMail API: https://javaee.github.io/javamail/
- JavaBeans Activation Framework: https://javaee.github.io/javabeans-activation-framework/

Here's a simple Java program that demonstrates peer-to-peer communication between a server and a client, sending and receiving a 10-byte message:

Server:

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;

public class PeerToPeerServer {

  public static void main(String[] args) {

    int portNumber = 4444;

    try {
      ServerSocket serverSocket = new ServerSocket(portNumber);
      System.out.println("Server started. Waiting for connection...");

      Socket clientSocket = serverSocket.accept();
      System.out.println("Client connected.");

      InputStream in = clientSocket.getInputStream();
      OutputStream out = clientSocket.getOutputStream();

      byte[] buffer = new byte[10];
      int numBytes = in.read(buffer);
      System.out.println("Received " + numBytes + " bytes from client: " + new String(buffer));

      out.write(buffer);
      System.out.println("Sent " + numBytes + " bytes to client.");

      clientSocket.close();
      serverSocket.close();
    } catch (IOException ex) {
      System.err.println("Error: " + ex.getMessage());
    }
  }

}
```

Client:

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;

public class PeerToPeerClient {

  public static void main(String[] args) {

    String hostName = "localhost";
    int portNumber = 4444;

    try {
      Socket clientSocket = new Socket(hostName, portNumber);
      System.out.println("Connected to server.");

      InputStream in = clientSocket.getInputStream();
      OutputStream out = clientSocket.getOutputStream();

      byte[] buffer = "Hello, world".getBytes();
      out.write(buffer);
      System.out.println("Sent " + buffer.length + " bytes to server.");

      buffer = new byte[10];
      int numBytes = in.read(buffer);
      System.out.println("Received " + numBytes + " bytes from server: " + new String(buffer));

      clientSocket.close();
    } catch (IOException ex) {
      System.err.println("Error: " + ex.getMessage());
    }
  }

}
```

The server program listens on port 4444 using a `ServerSocket` and waits for a client to connect. Once the client is connected, it reads a 10-byte message from the client using an `InputStream`, and sends the same message back to the client using an `OutputStream`. The server then closes the client socket and server socket.

The client program connects to the server using a `Socket`, and sends a 10-byte message to the server using an `OutputStream`. It then reads a 10-byte message from the server using an `InputStream`, and displays the message on the console. The client then closes the socket.

Here's a simple Java program that detects your public router IP address using a web-based API:

```java
import java.net.*;
import java.io.*;

public class DetectPublicIP {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    try {
      URL url = new URL("https://checkip.amazonaws.com/");
      BufferedReader in = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(url.openStream()));
      String ipAddress = in.readLine().trim();
      System.out.println("Public IP address: " + ipAddress);
    } catch (IOException ex) {
      System.err.println("Failed to detect public IP address: " + ex.getMessage());
    }
  }

}
```

The program sends a HTTP GET request to the URL "https://checkip.amazonaws.com/", which returns the client's public IP address as a plain text string. The program then reads the text string from the input stream using a `BufferedReader`, and displays it on the console.

Note that this program assumes that your router is configured with a public IP address, and that the web-based API is accessible from your network. If your router is configured with a private IP address behind a NAT (Network Address Translation) firewall, the public IP address returned by the API may be the IP address of the firewall or proxy server.

Yes, Java can detect the IP address of a device without using an external website service. Here's an example code that uses the `java.net` package to get the IP address:

```java
import java.net.*;

public class DetectIPAddress {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    try {
      InetAddress localHost = InetAddress.getLocalHost();
      String ipAddress = localHost.getHostAddress();
      System.out.println("IP address: " + ipAddress);
    } catch (UnknownHostException ex) {
      System.err.println("Failed to detect IP address: " + ex.getMessage());
    }
  }

}
```

The `InetAddress.getLocalHost()` method returns the IP address of the local machine as an `InetAddress` object. The `getHostAddress()` method of the `InetAddress` object returns the IP address as a `String`, which can be displayed on the console.

Here's a simple Java program that generates a random IPv4 and IPv6 address:

```java
import java.net.InetAddress;
import java.net.UnknownHostException;
import java.util.Random;

public class GenerateIPAddress {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            String ipv4Address = generateIPv4Address();
            String ipv6Address = generateIPv6Address();
            System.out.println("IPv4 address: " + ipv4Address);
            System.out.println("IPv6 address: " + ipv6Address);
        } catch (UnknownHostException ex) {
            System.err.println("Failed to generate IP address: " + ex.getMessage());
        }
    }

    private static String generateIPv4Address() throws UnknownHostException {
        Random random = new Random();
        byte[] ip = new byte[4];
        random.nextBytes(ip);
        InetAddress address = InetAddress.getByAddress(ip);
        return address.getHostAddress();
    }

    private static String generateIPv6Address() throws UnknownHostException {
        Random random = new Random();
        byte[] ip = new byte[16];
        random.nextBytes(ip);
        InetAddress address = InetAddress.getByAddress(ip);
        return address.getHostAddress();
    }

}
```

The `generateIPv4Address()` method generates a random array of 4 bytes using a `Random` object, creates a new `InetAddress` object from the byte array using the `getByAddress()` method, and returns the IP address as a string using the `getHostAddress()` method.

The `generateIPv6Address()` method is similar, but generates a random array of 16 bytes for an IPv6 address.

Note that the code may generate invalid or reserved IP addresses, depending on the random byte values generated. Also, the quality of randomness depends on the random number generator used.
